    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Coping With College</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Frederick J Streets, Yale University chaplain, letter on Oct 26 article about mental health counseling in college holds that campus clergy provide help to many students needing support while away from home; drawing (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Dorms May Be Great'': On many college campuses, the university chaplain counsels students, assesses their emotional needs and directs them to the school's mental health services.</p>
        <p>Often, emotionally troubled students or concerned parents and friends contact the campus clergy first. Campus ministers collaborate with various college staff and mental health professionals to learn from one another how best to serve students.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Dorms May Be Great'': On many college campuses, the university chaplain counsels students, assesses their emotional needs and directs them to the school's mental health services.</p>
        <p>Often, emotionally troubled students or concerned parents and friends contact the campus clergy first. Campus ministers collaborate with various college staff and mental health professionals to learn from one another how best to serve students.</p>
        <p>This method of sharing and, when appropriate, integrating spiritual support with psychiatric and other mental health services, is an effective and holistic way to address the emotional needs of students.</p>
        <p>FREDERICK J. STREETS  New Haven</p>
        <p>The writer, a clinical social worker, is chaplain of Yale.</p>
      </block>
